nub.core

Class Interpolator

  • java.lang.Object
    • nub.core.Interpolator

  • public class Interpolator
extends java.lang.Object
    A keyframe Catmull-Rom interpolator.

    An interpolator holds keyframes (that define a path) and, optionally, a reference to a node of your application (which will be interpolated). In this case, when the user call run(), an interpolator task() will regularly updates the node() position, orientation and magnitude along the path.

    Here is a typical usage example: 

     
 void setup() {
   Graph graph = new Graph(1200, 800);
   Interpolator interpolator = new Interpolator();
   for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++)
     interpolator.addKeyFrame(scene.randomNode());
   interpolator.run();
 }
    which will create a random (see Node.random(Graph)) interpolator path containing 10 keyframes (see addKeyFrame(Node)). The interpolation is also run (see run()). The interpolation is stopped when time() is greater than the lastTime() (unless enableRecurrence() is called).

    The interpolator visual representation may be configured using the following hints: SPLINE and STEPS. See hint(), configHint(int, Object...) enableHint(int), enableHint(int, Object...), disableHint(int), toggleHint(int) and resetHint(). Attention: If a Constraint is attached to the node() (see Node.constraint()), it should be reset before run() is called, otherwise the interpolated motion (computed as if there was no constraint) will probably be erroneous.

      • run

        public void run(int period,
                float speed)
        Starts the interpolation process.

        A task is started which will update the node()'s position, orientation and magnitude at the current time().

        If time() is larger than lastTime(), time() is reset to firstTime() before interpolation starts (and conversely for negative speed.

        Use setTime(float) before calling this method to change the starting time().

        Note that Task.isActive() will return true until Task.stop() is called.

        Attention: The keyframes must be defined (see addKeyFrame(Node, float)) before you start(), or else the interpolation will naturally immediately stop.

        See Also:
        run(), run(float)

      • reset

        public void reset()
        Stops the interpolation and resets time() to the firstTime().

        If desired, call interpolate(float) after this method to actually move the node() to firstTime().

      • setTime

        public void setTime(float time)
        Sets the time(). Attention: The node() state is not affected by this method. Use this function to define the starting time of a future interpolation (see run()). Use interpolate(float) to actually interpolate at a given time.

      • time

        public float time()
        Returns the current interpolation time (in seconds) along the interpolator path.

        This time is regularly updated when Task.isActive(). Can be set directly with setTime(float) or interpolate(float).

      • duration

        public float duration()

        Simply corresponds to lastTime() - firstTime(). Returns 0 if the path has less than 2 keyframes.

      • isRecurrent

        public boolean isRecurrent()
        Returns true when the interpolation is played in an infinite loop.

        When false (default), the interpolation stops when time() reaches firstTime() (with negative speed which is set with run(int, float)) or lastTime().

        time() is otherwise reset to firstTime() (+ time() - lastTime()) (and inversely for negative speed which is set with run(int, float)) and interpolation continues.

      • speed

        public float speed()
        Returns the current interpolation speed.

        Default value is 1, which means time() will be matched during the interpolation (provided that your main loop is fast enough).

        A negative value will result in a reverse interpolation of the keyframes.

        See Also:
        setSpeed(float), Task.period()

      • addKeyFrame

        public void addKeyFrame(Node node,
                        int hint,
                        float time)
        Appends a new keyframe which will display the node hint when the interpolator SPLINE hint is enabled, time seconds after the previously added one.

        Note that when node is modified, the interpolator path is updated accordingly. This allows for dynamic paths, where keyframes can be edited, even during the interpolation.

        null node references are silently ignored.

        See Also:
        addKeyFrame(Node, float), addKeyFrame(Node), addKeyFrame(int, float), addKeyFrame(float), addKeyFrame()

      • hint

        public int hint()
        Returns the current visual hint mask. The mask is a bitwise-or of the following single visual hints available the interpolator:

        1. SPLINE which displays a Catmull-Rom spline having the key-frames as its control points.
        2. STEPS which defines what to draw between consecutive key-frames.
        Displaying the hint requires first to enabling it (see enableHint(int)) and then calling either Graph.render(Node) or Graph.render(). Use configHint(int, Object...) to configure the hint different visual aspects.
        See Also:
        enableHint(int), configHint(int, Object...), enableHint(int, Object...), disableHint(int), toggleHint(int), isHintEnabled(int), resetHint()

      • resetHint

        public void resetHint()

      • configHint

        public void configHint(int hint,
                       java.lang.Object... params)
        Configures the hint using varargs as follows:

        1. SPLINE hint: configHint(Interpolator.SPLINE, splineStroke).
        2. SPLINE hint: configHint(Interpolator.SPLINE, splineStroke, splineWeight).
        3. STEPS hint: configHint(Interpolator.STEPS, hint).
        Note that the splineStroke is a color int var;splineWeight is a stroke weight int var; and, hint is a node Node.hint() defining what to draw between two consecutives key-frames. See also setSteps(int).
        See Also:
        hint(), enableHint(int), enableHint(int, Object...), disableHint(int), toggleHint(int), isHintEnabled(int), resetHint()
